  "description": "Diffie-Hellman lets two parties derive a shared secret over a public channel: they agree on public parameters, each picks a private exponent and exchanges its public power, then both compute the same shared value; because passive eavesdroppers cannot, but active attackers can, the exchange must be authenticated to resist man-in-the-middle.",
